Importing Data

library(fpp2)

data("arrivals")
ts_data <- arrivals[, "US"]  # Extract US arrivals
ts_data <- ts(ts_data, start = c(1981, 1), frequency = 12)

Time Series Plot

ggplot2::autoplot(ts_data) +
  ggtitle("US Arrivals to Australia") +
  xlab("Year") +
  ylab("Number of Arrivals")

Observations: - There appears to be an increasing trend over time. - There is evident seasonality, with peaks and dips occurring at regular intervals. - Some fluctuations are more extreme in certain periods.

Summary Statistics

summary(ts_data)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   23.72   63.95   85.88   84.85  108.98  136.09
boxplot(ts_data, main="Boxplot of US Arrivals to Australia", ylab="Arrivals")

Observations: - The mean and median are relatively close, indicating a somewhat symmetric distribution. - There are potential outliers in the upper range. - Seasonality likely contributes to the variations in values.

Time Series Decomposition

decomp <- decompose(ts_data, type = "multiplicative")
plot(decomp)

Observations: - The series exhibits a clear seasonal pattern. - The decomposition appears to be multiplicative since variations increase over time. - Seasonality indices reveal months with high and low arrivals.

decomp$seasonal[1:12]  # Extract seasonal indices
##  [1] 1.1040433 0.9059589 0.9048643 1.0716996 1.0550003 0.9040813 1.0148999
##  [8] 1.0898170 1.0640138 0.9162763 0.9095888 1.0597566
  • The highest arrivals occur in December (holiday season).
  • The lowest arrivals occur in February, likely due to fewer vacations.

Seasonality-Adjusted Plot

adjusted_ts <- ts_data / decomp$seasonal
autoplot(ts_data, series="Actual") +
  autolayer(adjusted_ts, series="Seasonally Adjusted", color='red') +
  ggtitle("Seasonally Adjusted vs. Actual US Arrivals")

Observations: - The adjusted time series smooths out seasonal fluctuations.

Nave Method Forecast

naive_model <- naive(ts_data)
plot(naive_model)

Residual Analysis

residuals <- residuals(naive_model)

# Plot Residuals
autoplot(residuals) + ggtitle("Residuals Plot")

# Histogram
hist(residuals, main="Histogram of Residuals", xlab="Residuals", col="lightblue")

# Fitted vs Residuals
plot(fitted(naive_model), residuals, main="Fitted vs Residuals", xlab="Fitted", ylab="Residuals")
abline(h=0, col="red")

# Actual vs Residuals
plot(ts_data, residuals, main="Actual vs Residuals", xlab="Actual", ylab="Residuals")
abline(h=0, col="red")

# ACF Plot
Acf(residuals)

Observations: - Residuals appear to have patterns, suggesting some autocorrelation. - The histogram suggests normality but with slight skewness. - The ACF plot indicates potential correlation in residuals.

Forecasting Accuracy

accuracy(naive_model)

##                    ACF1

Final Forecast

naive_forecast <- naive(arrivals[,4])
plot(naive_forecast)

plot(residuals(naive_forecast))

hist(residuals(naive_forecast))

plot(fitted(naive_forecast), residuals(naive_forecast))

plot(naive_forecast$x, residuals(naive_forecast))

Acf(residuals(naive_forecast), main="ACF Plot of Residuals")

##### Nave forecast is not a good forecasting model for the data.
